Based on the meeting transcript, here's how to explain the DevSecOps project in an interview:

Project Overview:
"I implemented a DevSecOps project where we deployed a 3-tier application (frontend, backend, and database) with integrated security scanning tools in the CI/CD pipeline."

Key Components:

Infrastructure Setup: Set up Jenkins on AWS EC2 (Ubuntu, t2.large instance with 50GB storage)

Security Tools Integrated:

SonarQube: For code quality checking - identifies bugs, code duplication, vulnerabilities, and ensures code standards
Trivy: For container image scanning - scans Docker images for security vulnerabilities (critical, medium, low severity issues)
GitLeaks: For detecting code leaks and sensitive information in the code
Pipeline Configuration:

Installed Jenkins plugins (Docker, SonarQube Scanner, Pipeline)
Configured Docker integration for building and pushing images
Set up SonarQube server with webhook integration to Jenkins
Used token-based authentication between Jenkins and SonarQube
Application Architecture:

Frontend running on port 5000
Backend application
MySQL database on port 3000
All components containerized using Docker
Important Interview Points:

Don't claim you did everything alone - mention "with the help of senior team members, we implemented DevSecOps pipelines"
Explain that security scans (SonarQube, Trivy) are not run on every build due to performance and cost considerations - only when code is finalized for production
Database queries were used to check application data, user logins, and troubleshoot issues
Security gates were configured - if critical vulnerabilities exceeded a threshold (e.g., more than 5 critical issues), the pipeline would fail
Real-time Use Case:
The project ensured that security vulnerabilities were caught before production deployment, improving software quality and reducing production-level security issues.
