Based on the context from today's session, here are the key Q&A points discussed:

DevSecOps Project Topics:

Difference between DevOps and DevSecOps: In DevSecOps, all security and vulnerability issues must be fixed before production deployment, not on the fly
Tools covered: Trivy (image scanning), GitLeaks (code leak detection), SonarQube (code quality check), CheckOV (Infrastructure as Code security scanning)
Technical Implementation:

Created EC2 instance (Project 7) with Ubuntu 24.04 LTS
Installed Jenkins, Docker, and SonarQube
Configured ports: 8080 (Jenkins), 9000 (SonarQube), 5000, 3000
Set up integrations between Jenkins, Docker, and SonarQube using tokens and credentials
Implemented Trivy for vulnerability scanning of Docker images
Key Interview Questions Discussed:

Cost optimization: Check server utilization (CPU/memory usage vs allocated resources), use CloudWatch metrics, analyze 6-month history, resize instances if underutilized, shutdown dev/QA environments during weekends
Remote vs Local state in Terraform: Remote state stored in S3 (centralized), local state on local system; configured using backend block
Terraform workspace: Used to switch between environments (dev/prod) without changing main configuration files
Server troubleshooting: Check logs and alerts first before restarting; if server won't start, detach volumes and create new instance
Additional Points:

SonarQube checks: Code quality, duplication, bugs, standards, syntax issues
Quality gates determine if code passes security standards
Don't run security scans on every CI build due to cost and performance considerations
The session emphasized practical implementation of DevSecOps tools and real-world troubleshooting scenarios.
